      Ketchup Caddy
   =20
 =20

Demand response is the business of getting paid for not using electricity. =
You might think that would sometimes lead to fraud, and oh does it. Here is=
 the story of someone who allegedly committed fraud by signing up fake cust=
omers, promising that they would cut back their electricity use, and then g=
etting paid even though they didn=E2=80=99t.
First, a very stylized sketch of the electric grid. In the US, there are se=
veral regional electric grids that transmit electricity from power provider=
s to users and are=C2=A0run by=C2=A0organizations with=C2=A0names like MISO=
 (Midcontinent Independent System Operator) or ERCOT (Electric Reliability =
Council of Texas). Various providers =E2=80=94=C2=A0power plants, etc. =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0sell power to the grid, and much thought goes into the auction =
mechanisms that match supply and demand and determine how much the provider=
s get paid.
A key problem is that the demand for power fluctuates from hour to hour, wh=
ile the supply of power is more or less capped over the medium term by the =
capacity of the power plants connected to the grid.=C2=A0At peak times, the=
 grid has to call on every available resource =E2=80=94 always-on nuclear p=
lants, whatever wind is blowing, gas peaker plants, obsolescent coal power =
plants, capacity from neighboring grids,=C2=A0batteries, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0to meet demand. But it might not be economical to own and operate a powe=
r plant that only gets turned on, like, two hours a year. And so much thoug=
ht also goes into figuring out how to make sure there will be=C2=A0enough c=
apacity to meet peak demand.
Here are two=C2=A0methods to do that. One is  capacity payments, where powe=
r suppliers can get paid some amount of money just for committing to turn o=
n their plants if they=E2=80=99re needed. If the plants are never needed, t=
hey never turn on, but the suppliers are paid for the commitment, which mak=
es it more economical to keep the plants around, which makes=C2=A0the grid =
more reliable. (In MISO, the grid operator for some of the middle of the US=
, these payments are set by an annual =E2=80=9CPlanning Resource Auction,=
=E2=80=9D or PRA.)
The other is demand response. At some point, it occurred to some genius of =
electricity economics that=C2=A0turning off your air conditioner, at times =
of peak electric=C2=A0demand, is just as good as=C2=A0generating=C2=A0a bit=
 more power.=C2=A0If you are a=C2=A0user=C2=A0of power, and you agree to=C2=
=A0stop=C2=A0using power at peak times, that=E2=80=99s as valuable to the g=
rid as generating power would be, and so the grid operator will pay you for=
 the power you don=E2=80=99t use. If you run a factory that normally uses 1=
0 megawatts, and you shut down the factory for an hour of peak demand, the =
grid could pay you as though you generated 10 megawatt-hours. Just like a p=
ower plant operator, you can get paid the market rate for peak electricity =
for curtailing your use =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you can also get capacity paymen=
ts for=C2=A0promising=C2=A0to curtail your use if necessary.
You can easily imagine how this might lead to fraud. Here=E2=80=99s the way=
 I have always imagined it might lead to fraud. Demand response is essentia=
lly counterfactual: You get paid for how much electricity you=C2=A0would=C2=
=A0have used=C2=A0but didn=E2=80=99t. So the more electricity you=C2=A0say=
=C2=A0you would have used, the more you get paid. You can=E2=80=99t literal=
ly just write down =E2=80=9CI would have used 10 megawatts, so pay me,=E2=
=80=9D but you have some baseline measurement of what you would have used, =
and if you  manipulate that baseline=C2=A0then maybe you can manipulate you=
r payout.
  [1]

But there is a much funnier way to do demand response fraud. Demand respons=
e is generally a business of middlemen: Demand-response intermediaries (or =
=E2=80=9Caggregators=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0enter deals with consumers or factory o=
wners or whoever to curtail their usage if called upon, and then the aggreg=
ators=C2=A0enter deals with the grid operators to deliver that curtailment.=
 The grid pays the aggregators =E2=80=94=C2=A0in the form of capacity payme=
nts for=C2=A0committing=C2=A0to curtail usage, and/or in the form of curtai=
lment payments for actually cutting back electricity use =E2=80=94=C2=A0and=
 the aggregators share some of the payments with the customers.=C2=A0
Again, the capacity payments get made even if the customers are never asked=
 to cut back their electricity use: The point is to make the electric grid =
more reliable by making sure that there is enough capacity to handle peak l=
oads, even if that capacity is never actually used. So! The trade is:
=09Be a demand-response aggregator, a middleman between the electric grid a=
nd customers willing to cut back on usage at peak times.=09
Don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0sign up any customers.=09Instead, just write down a bunc=
h of fake customers=E2=80=99 names =E2=80=94=C2=A0or rather, names of real =
people who are not your customers =E2=80=94=C2=A0and offer their capacity t=
o the grid.=09Receive capacity payments.=09If the grid operator never asks =
you to deliver power, terrific: You keep the capacity payments, and you don=
=E2=80=99t have to share them=C2=A0with your =E2=80=9Ccustomers,=E2=80=9D w=
ho don=E2=80=99t even know about any of this.=09If the grid operator=C2=A0d=
oes=C2=A0ask you to deliver power, oops.

I mean, that=E2=80=99s the schematic funny version. The real version is in =
 this Federal Energy Regulatory Commission enforcement action=C2=A0(via  Ut=
ility Dive) and it is even funnier, starting with the names. The company th=
at allegedly did this fraud is called Ketchup Caddy LLC, and its founder an=
d chief executive officer is=C2=A0named Philip Mango. Mango learned (at lun=
ch with an employee of =E2=80=9CCompany A,=E2=80=9D another demand-response=
 aggregator)=C2=A0that you could just go to the website of Ameren Illinois =
Co. (a retail power company)=C2=A0and scrape the names of its customers, an=
d he got his friend =E2=80=94=C2=A0a computer programmer named Todd Meiners=
hagen =E2=80=94=C2=A0to do that:
To do this, he created an automated tool that accessed Ameren=E2=80=99s web=
site, bombarded the website with millions of random account numbers until i=
t located a valid customer account, and then downloaded the account data to=
 a spreadsheet.
Terrific. Mango explained to Meinershagen that he would use that list =E2=
=80=94=C2=A0of people who use electricity =E2=80=94 to go out and solicit c=
ustomers for Ketchup Caddy=E2=80=99s demand-response business, at terms tha=
t were very favorable to Ketchup Caddy:
Specifically, Mango told Meinershagen =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthat my job w=
as to acquire customers that [Meinershagen] had scraped through legitimate =
means, getting them to agree to be part of the program and accepting a term=
 of 100 percent payout to us, zero percent payout for them. In return, my p=
itch that I explained to Todd [Meinershagen] and how I was able to do that =
was by saying that they were participating in getting green credits being s=
ustainable, and he accepted that explanation.=E2=80=9D
Sure! =E2=80=9CGreen credits.=E2=80=9D But in fact Mango never called any c=
ustomers, in part because that would be a lot of work and in part because n=
o customers would actually agree to a deal in which they promised to turn o=
ff their air conditioners and=C2=A0Ketchup Caddy got all the payments. Inst=
ead, he just submitted the fake list of customers to MISO, the grid operato=
r:
In late February 2019 ... Ketchup Caddy was accepted to participate in MISO=
=E2=80=99s annual PRA.=C2=A0To register its purported customers to particip=
ate, Ketchup Caddy had to provide certain data about them to MISO. To obtai=
n this data, Mango selected a set of customers from the data that Meinersha=
gen=E2=80=99s scraping tool had illicitly collected from Ameren=E2=80=99s w=
ebsite. He then had Meinershagen create =E2=80=9Ccurtailment plans=E2=80=9D=
 for these customers based on a [Company A] document provided to Ketchup Ca=
ddy by Company A Employee 1. To do this, Meinershagen reviewed the data fro=
m Ameren=E2=80=99s website for instances in which a customer=E2=80=99s ener=
gy usage dropped during a 1-2 hour period, and then provided Mango with two=
 graphs consisting of =E2=80=9Ca week with the lowest hour of energy usage =
and one with the max hour of energy usage.=E2=80=9D Mango testified that th=
ese graphs reflected =E2=80=9Cmock test=E2=80=9D information, =E2=80=9C[i]n=
 other words, not a real test of the facility but a graphical representatio=
n of a load drop that could be performed, if called upon.=E2=80=9D Mango al=
so testified that, despite submitting this =E2=80=9Cmock test=E2=80=9D info=
rmation to MISO, he knew that these customers would not perform if called u=
pon.
MISO rejected some of Ketchup Caddy=E2=80=99s fake customers because they w=
ere=C2=A0actual=C2=A0customers of other demand-response aggregators,=C2=A0b=
ut despite noticing that red flag, it let the rest of the customers through=
