</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;"><a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/34493478.285379/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuaWVhLm9yZy9lbmVyZ3ktc3lzdGVtL2Vu=
ZXJneS1lZmZpY2llbmN5LWFuZC1kZW1hbmQvZGVtYW5kLXJlc3BvbnNl/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB2ac1e3e4" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">Demand response</a> is the business of getting pai=
d for not using electricity. You might think that would sometimes lead to f=
raud, and oh does it. Here is the story of someone who allegedly committed =
fraud by signing up fake customers, promising that they would cut back thei=
r electricity use, and then getting paid even though they didn=E2=80=99t.</=
p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First, a very stylized sketch of the electric =
grid. In the US, there are several regional electric grids that transmit el=
ectricity from power providers to users and are=C2=A0run by=C2=A0organizati=
ons with=C2=A0names like MISO (Midcontinent Independent System Operator) or=
 ERCOT (Electric Reliability Council of Texas). Various providers =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0power plants, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0sell power to the grid, and much th=
ought goes into the auction mechanisms that match supply and demand and det=
ermine how much the providers get paid.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A key problem is that the demand for power flu=
ctuates from hour to hour, while the supply of power is more or less capped=
 over the medium term by the capacity of the power plants connected to the =
grid.=C2=A0At peak times, the grid has to call on every available resource =
=E2=80=94 always-on nuclear plants, whatever wind is blowing, gas peaker pl=
ants, obsolescent coal power plants, capacity from neighboring grids,=C2=A0=
batteries, etc. =E2=80=94=C2=A0to meet demand. But it might not be economic=
al to own and operate a power plant that only gets turned on, like, two hou=
rs a year. And so much thought also goes into figuring out how to make sure=
 there will be=C2=A0enough capacity to meet peak demand.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are two=C2=A0methods to do that. One is <=
a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34493478.285379/aHR=
0cHM6Ly9lbmVyZ3luZXdzLnVzLzIwMTMvMDYvMTcvZXhwbGFpbmVyLWhvdy1jYXBhY2l0eS1tYX=
JrZXRzLXdvcmsv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB102e7f2f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> capacity payment=
s</a>, where power suppliers can get paid some amount of money just for <em=
>committing</em> to turn on their plants if they=E2=80=99re needed. If the =
plants are never needed, they never turn on, but the suppliers are paid for=
 the commitment, which makes it more economical to keep the plants around, =
which makes=C2=A0the grid more reliable. (In MISO, the grid operator for so=
me of the middle of the US, these payments are set by an annual =E2=80=9C<a=
 href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34493478.285379/aHR0=
cHM6Ly9jZG4ubWlzb2VuZXJneS5vcmcvMjAyMyUyMFBsYW5uaW5nJTIwUmVzb3VyY2UlMjBBdWN=
0aW9uJTIwKFBSQSklMjBSZXN1bHRzNjI4OTI1LnBkZg/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB98b3a0=
0f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=
=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: =
1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-c=
olor: #ccc;">Planning Resource Auction</a>,=E2=80=9D or PRA.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other is demand response. At some point, i=
t occurred to some genius of electricity economics that=C2=A0<em>turning of=
f your air conditioner</em>, at times of peak electric=C2=A0demand, is just=
 as good as=C2=A0<em>generating=C2=A0</em>a bit more power.=C2=A0If you are=
 a=C2=A0<em>user=C2=A0</em>of power, and you agree to=C2=A0<em>stop=C2=A0</=
em>using power at peak times, that=E2=80=99s as valuable to the grid as gen=
erating power would be, and so the grid operator will pay you for the power=
 you don=E2=80=99t use. If you run a factory that normally uses 10 megawatt=
s, and you shut down the factory for an hour of peak demand, the grid could=
 pay you as though you generated 10 megawatt-hours. Just like a power plant=
 operator, you can get paid the market rate for peak electricity for curtai=
ling your use =E2=80=94=C2=A0and you can also get capacity payments for=C2=
=A0<em>promising=C2=A0</em>to curtail your use if necessary.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">You can easily imagine how this might lead to =
fraud. Here=E2=80=99s the way I have always imagined it might lead to fraud=
. Demand response is essentially counterfactual: You get paid for how much =
electricity you=C2=A0<em>would=C2=A0</em>have used=C2=A0but didn=E2=80=99t.=
 So the more electricity you=C2=A0<em>say=C2=A0</em>you would have used, th=
e more you get paid. You can=E2=80=99t literally just write down =E2=80=9CI=
 would have used 10 megawatts, so pay me,=E2=80=9D but you have some baseli=
ne measurement of what you would have used, and if you <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/34493478.285379/aHR0cHM6Ly9pZWVleHBsb3=
JlLmllZWUub3JnL2RvY3VtZW50Lzk2NTY5NTI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB9bf69e4d" it=
emprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"col=
or: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bo=
rder-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #=
ccc;"> manipulate that baseline</a>=C2=A0then maybe you can manipulate your=
 payout.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #0=
00000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-b=
ottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-colo=
r: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a></p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But there is a much funnier way to do demand r=
esponse fraud. Demand response is generally a business of middlemen: Demand=
-response intermediaries (or =E2=80=9Caggregators=E2=80=9D)=C2=A0enter deal=
s with consumers or factory owners or whoever to curtail their usage if cal=
led upon, and then the aggregators=C2=A0enter deals with the grid operators=
 to deliver that curtailment. The grid pays the aggregators =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
in the form of capacity payments for=C2=A0<em>committing=C2=A0</em>to curta=
il usage, and/or in the form of curtailment payments for actually cutting b=
ack electricity use =E2=80=94=C2=A0and the aggregators share some of the pa=
yments with the customers.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, the capacity payments get made even if =
the customers are never asked to cut back their electricity use: The point =
is to make the electric grid more reliable by making sure that there is eno=
ugh capacity to handle peak loads, even if that capacity is never actually =
used. So! The trade is:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Be a demand-response aggregator, a mi=
ddleman between the electric grid and customers willing to cut back on usag=
e at peak times.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">
<em>Don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>sign up any customers.</li>=09<li style=3D"marg=
in-bottom: 5px;">Instead, just write down a bunch of fake customers=E2=80=
=99 names =E2=80=94=C2=A0or rather, names of real people who are not your c=
ustomers =E2=80=94=C2=A0and offer their capacity to the grid.</li>=09<li st=
yle=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Receive capacity payments.</li>=09<li style=3D"=
margin-bottom: 5px;">If the grid operator never asks you to deliver power, =
terrific: You keep the capacity payments, and you don=E2=80=99t have to sha=
re them=C2=A0with your =E2=80=9Ccustomers,=E2=80=9D who don=E2=80=99t even =
know about any of this.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If the gri=
d operator=C2=A0<em>does=C2=A0</em>ask you to deliver power, oops.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I mean, that=E2=80=99s the schematic funny ver=
sion. The real version is in <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/34493478.285379/aHR0cHM6Ly9jbXMuZmVyYy5nb3YvbWVkaWEvMjAyNDAyMjEt=
MTg2ZmVyYzYxMTMyLWluMjMtMTQtMDAwLWtldGNodXAtY2FkZHktZXQtYWwtb3Nj/607f07ceef=
4b8524a319a23cB4c0dd223" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" tar=
get=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; b=
order-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style:=
 solid; background-color: #ccc;"> this Federal Energy Regulatory Commission=
 enforcement action</a>=C2=A0(via <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/34493478.285379/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cudXRpbGl0eWRpdmUuY29tL25ld3M=
vZmVyYy1lbmZvcmNlbWVudC1rZXRjaHVwLWNhZGR5LW1pc28tbWFya2V0LW1hbmlwdWxhdGluZy=
83MDgxODMv/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBc128397d" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemsc=
ope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> Utility Dive</a>) an=
d it is even funnier, starting with the names. The company that allegedly d=
id this fraud is called Ketchup Caddy LLC, and its founder and chief execut=
ive officer is=C2=A0named Philip Mango. Mango learned (at lunch with an emp=
loyee of =E2=80=9CCompany A,=E2=80=9D another demand-response aggregator)=
=C2=A0that you could just go to the website of Ameren Illinois Co. (a retai=
l power company)=C2=A0and scrape the names of its customers, and he got his=
 friend =E2=80=94=C2=A0a computer programmer named Todd Meinershagen =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0to do that:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To do this, he created an automate=
d tool that accessed Ameren=E2=80=99s website, bombarded the website with m=
illions of random account numbers until it located a valid customer account=
, and then downloaded the account data to a spreadsheet.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Terrific. Mango explained to Meinershagen that=
 he would use that list =E2=80=94=C2=A0of people who use electricity =E2=80=
=94 to go out and solicit customers for Ketchup Caddy=E2=80=99s demand-resp=
onse business, at terms that were very favorable to Ketchup Caddy:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Specifically, Mango told Meinersha=
gen =E2=80=A6=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cthat my job was to acquire customers that [Mein=
ershagen] had scraped through legitimate means, getting them to agree to be=
 part of the program and accepting a term of 100 percent payout to us, zero=
 percent payout for them. In return, my pitch that I explained to Todd [Mei=
nershagen] and how I was able to do that was by saying that they were parti=
cipating in getting green credits being sustainable, and he accepted that e=
xplanation.=E2=80=9D</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Sure! =E2=80=9CGreen credits.=E2=80=9D But in =
fact Mango never called any customers, in part because that would be a lot =
of work and in part because no customers would actually agree to a deal in =
which they promised to turn off their air conditioners and=C2=A0Ketchup Cad=
dy got all the payments. Instead, he just submitted the fake list of custom=
ers to MISO, the grid operator:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In late February 2019 ... Ketchup =
Caddy was accepted to participate in MISO=E2=80=99s annual PRA.=C2=A0To reg=
ister its purported customers to participate, Ketchup Caddy had to provide =
certain data about them to MISO. To obtain this data, Mango selected a set =
of customers from the data that Meinershagen=E2=80=99s scraping tool had il=
licitly collected from Ameren=E2=80=99s website. He then had Meinershagen c=
reate =E2=80=9Ccurtailment plans=E2=80=9D for these customers based on a [C=
ompany A] document provided to Ketchup Caddy by Company A Employee 1. To do=
 this, Meinershagen reviewed the data from Ameren=E2=80=99s website for ins=
tances in which a customer=E2=80=99s energy usage dropped during a 1-2 hour=
 period, and then provided Mango with two graphs consisting of =E2=80=9Ca w=
eek with the lowest hour of energy usage and one with the max hour of energ=
y usage.=E2=80=9D Mango testified that these graphs reflected =E2=80=9Cmock=
 test=E2=80=9D information, =E2=80=9C[i]n other words, not a real test of t=
he facility but a graphical representation of a load drop that could be per=
formed, if called upon.=E2=80=9D Mango also testified that, despite submitt=
ing this =E2=80=9Cmock test=E2=80=9D information to MISO, he knew that thes=
e customers would not perform if called upon.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">MISO rejected some of Ketchup Caddy=E2=80=99s =
fake customers because they were=C2=A0<em>actual=C2=A0</em>customers of oth=
er demand-response aggregators,=C2=A0but despite noticing that red flag, it=
 let the rest of the customers through and started paying Ketchup Caddy for=
 hundreds of megawatts of capacity. This went on for about three years, and=
 Ketchup Caddy got about $1 million of capacity payments. The fake customer=
s got nothing. Also, no harm, no foul, ish:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because MISO did not call a curtai=
lment event in any of these Planning Years and required only mock tests to =
verify performance, Ketchup Caddy=E2=80=99s false registrations and offers =
did not come to light until Staff=E2=80=99s Investigation.</p></blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">They sold fake power capacity to the grid for =
three years, but nobody noticed, because they were never called on to deliv=
er that power.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Anyway, great fraud. Apparently Meinershagen w=
as totally innocent:</p>
<blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Unlike Mango, Staff found no evide=
nce that Meinershagen was expressly aware that Mango had been registering c=
ustomers with MISO for Ketchup Caddy without their consent.=C2=A0In fact, M=
ango testified that he kept Meinershagen =E2=80=9Cin the dark=E2=80=9D and =
created a =E2=80=9Cmirage=E2=80=9D to make Meinershagen believe that their =
company was formally engaging with its purported customers.</p></blockquote=
>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile, Mango was hilariously candid with t=
he FERC staff who investigated him:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mango explained that his decision to operate h=
is business in this manner was based on his understanding that =E2=80=9C[Co=
mpany A] is doing this. They must have figured out something that I don=E2=
=80=99t, like this is essentially free money, no harm to the customer.=E2=
=80=9D He said he planned to =E2=80=9C[d]o this for just a couple of years,=
 make a bunch of money to put kids through school and do all those things, =
and no one=E2=80=99s hurt. Do it with the least amount of resource possible=
, the least amount of money invested.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Mango also testified that the idea of enrollin=
g customers with MISO and not sharing payments with them seemed a little to=
o good to be true, but that he justified it as follows: =E2=80=9CMy logic a=
t the time was that if it wasn=E2=80=99t too good to be true, that at some =
point in this year-long process of trying to get into the market something =
will stop us, something will trigger and that will be my =E2=80=94=C2=A0as =
naive as this sounds =E2=80=94 that will be my sign that this is not meant =
to be.=E2=80=9D</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I think that is probably part of the explanati=
on of a lot of frauds? =E2=80=9CIf I=E2=80=99m really not allowed to do thi=
s, probably someone will stop me before I actually do it,=E2=80=9D you thin=
k, and then nobody stops you before you do it, so you do it, and then they =
stop you=C2=A0<em>after=C2=A0</em>you did it, when it=E2=80=99s much worse.=
 The FERC wants Ketchup Caddy and Mango to pay $27 million of penalties and=
 disgorgement.</p>
